Open a C/C++ source file and notice that identifiers that are defined in C/C++ headers are being flagged as not found (seeing an underline under each symbol). Selecting "Problems" from the view menu displays these identifiers as undefined. 

This occurred only after I updated the C/C++ plugin. Never had this issue before that.

I used the snippet below to repro, but can repro this with multiple C/C++ files. 
---

Steps to Reproduce:

1. Enter the code below and note that "cout" and "endl" are flagged as undefined symbols. 

#include <iostream>

using namespace std;

int main()
{
  if (true)
  {
    // Testing
  }
  cout << "Testing" << endl;
  return 0;
}

We noticed a regression in the Haxe extension's metadata completion (https://github.com/vshaxe/vshaxe/issues/121). The issue first appeared in the March release (1.11.0), more specifically https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/commit/264908a434e98f9b22f8de358b3636200c332ea4 (isolated using `git bisect`). It can be reproduced with this code:

```ts
'use strict';
import * as vscode from 'vscode';

export function activate(context: vscode.ExtensionContext) {
    vscode.languages.registerCompletionItemProvider('foo', {
        provideCompletionItems(doc, pos) {
            return [new vscode.CompletionItem(':foo'), new vscode.CompletionItem(':Foo')];
        }
    }, "@", ":");
}
```

Somehow `:foo` is missing here, while `:Foo` still matches.

![](http://i.imgur.com/5iXbjfS.png)

Compare this with the behavior in the February release:

![](http://i.imgur.com/h4dJIci.png)

Note: I realize that this is fixed by removing the `:` trigger character, but this is necessary in the Haxe extension to provide completion for type hints. Related issue: #12772
